My thought process isn't very precise. Basically that states will be working to keep R0 at or slightly below 1.0. So the most likely answer is in the neighborhood of 50% of "States" (which inexplicably now includes DC but not the other things that aren't states by any reasonable definition of the word. It's a different list every time. Why?). Also that the spread is likely to skew toward the low side because people are targeting less than 1.0. And finally I'm noting that the buckets are not all the same size so need adjustment.

Just over 3 weeks ago there were 18 states that met this criteria. None of them have dropped below 1.0, but 15 others have joined them, putting the total at 33. Many states continue to reopen, schools are returning to in person classes, there remains no comprehensive and coordinated testing system at the federal level, large public gatherings, events, and parties are becoming more common and acceptable, and there is evidence that many Americans have grown bored of worrying about the pandemic. All of these means more people will likely get it, spread it, and die from it, suggesting the Rt value is unlikely to drop below 1.0 in many of the states currently struggling without the release of a vaccine or other artificial inhibitor.

Shifting to a more optimistic weighting. Jan 11 is nearly four months away, and a lot can happen between now and then. I'm going with the theory that specific resistance will continue to increase, including possibly from a vaccine. Rt could surprise on the downside.

Think of Rt in terms of trend of active cases. When the number of active cases is falling, Rt is below 1, When the number of active cases is increasing Rt is above 1. i.e. currently NY case trend is flat so the Rt is 1, AZ case trend is downwards so the Rt is 0.87

Rt can only be estimated, and it turns out not that precisely. Compare the numbers for July 23, when Rt.live estimated that there were 39 states with Rt >= 1.00. [I save the web pages so that I can check the old data.] Today, August 23, the Rt for one month ago is 18. The number of states with Rt >= 1.00 decreased by over 50%. On any given day the Rt values are only first estimates, and they can change dramatically over time as more information becomes available. The errors bands are widest for the first estimates.

At the moment, there are 18 states with an estimated Rt at or over 1.0 according to https://rt.live/. However, all but 2 states (Alabama and Arizona) have 1.0 within the margin of error for their estimations, meaning the number over 1.0 right now could potentially be as high as 48 out of 50 states. Moreover, many states have leveled out near the 1.0 mark (either above or below) in recent months as shelter in place orders have been lifted and reopening has begun. Both the federal government and many state governors have openly denounced the idea of shutting down the economy again, meaning that these numbers are unlikely to decrease very soon. In fact, it appears the only real precaution still in effect is the social norm of mask wearing, which is still not required by federal law or, indeed, openly encouraged by many state and federal politicians. Moreover, the WHO has just announced it hopes the pandemic to be over in... 2 years. This signals that we are unlikely to see a sudden drop to 0 any time soon without policy changes and more aggressive mitigation techniques. As such, I believe it will likely remain around current levels for the coming months, with potential random fluctuations up and down due to random error and unforeseen events (ex: school reopenings, large public gatherings, etc.) that could have detrimental effects on local communities.

The nature of Rt makes this particularly tricky value to predict, as it is calculated by how many people someone passes the infection on to. [1] Even if covid is under control in a state one super spreader event can raise this number significantly.

The Rt rate is kind of an odd measure to predict. Looking through the website FAQ, it's clear that what it is measures is the rate at which the number of cases is increasing. If a state has 1 person infected and that person infects 6, the state's Rt is 6, whereas a state that has 10000 cases and 1000 new cases has an Rt of .1. So we're not predicting cases but the rate of infections given the caseload. For example, NH has hovered around .9 to 1 for the past 4 months despite averaging like 60 new cases a day. NJ has been at exactly 1 despite being at 1/3 of their max cases.

1) The biology of the virus does not change to become less infective and if anything could POSSIBLY evolve to become more infective although this is unlikely. 2) Human nature can change which includes social distancing measures and mask wearing. 3) With school returning in the fall we will have altered some of these human measures to reduce reproductive rate. 4) Infections will continue to occur into the coming year. 5) I foresee an overall increase of knowledge and normalcy in implementing human behavior changes which will likely decrease the number of states that have a >1.0 Rt than what we have now but as history has shown us thus far, states may bounce back and forth. 6) Number of states will likely be less than 20 but I doubt the number of states to be less than 8 which would indicate a fizzling out of the pandemic in >42 states. Also, with increased infections, we presumbably have increased immunity, further decreasing Rt but I believe that that we would need a much higher Rt to induce herd immunity within 5 months.

It's almost impossible to continue at +1 for very long...you start running out of people to infect in about 2-3 months. Texas case is useful to see the numbers. The narrative is that TX cases are EXPLODING because the the state recklessly opened early. TX is averaging something like 70k tests daily, and can barely keep it at 1. So even when testing everybody who will hold still, even though hospitalization rates are dropping, the RT has trouble holding up. There would have to be a colossal second wave and mass reinfections in order to keep us in the positive range. see https://rt.live/us/TX.

Aug 18 there are 21 who meet the criteria, down from 40 some 2 months ago. New cases are slowing reducing Rt. The target is 5 months out when the US will be in peak flu season which may exacerbate Covid-19 infections. Most states exhibit an L shaped curve, with exceptions that are more like a W. As the disease progresses thru the population the R should decline, unless reinfection is rampant. Currently reinfection is the exception, not the rule.

Most States seem to be pertubating around 1. So I deem all outcomes more or less equally likely. I think the chances of having a vaccine with an impact on R0 are about 1% , therefore 7 or fewer is most likely...

Being through their "worst fall ever" with regards to public health, on the one hand there will be some limited form of natural herd immunity (maybe 30 to 40% of total US population will have had a COVID-19 infection by January 2021, confirmed or unconfirmed), on the other hand limited approved vaccine trials (up to 5% of total US population) could bring about some protection, while at the same time anyone who is neither immune nor vaccinated by that time will look after himself very carefully, as more and more damage done by an infection to the body will be known, and new SARS-CoV-2 strains might complicate things, by causing more harmful or more aggressive infections.
